article.description: Lauren Jackson nailed a bank shot with 3.5 seconds left that helped lift the Seattle Storm to a thrilling 67-65 victory over the Connecticut Sun in Sue Bird's return to the state where she won a pair of national championships in college.
article.headline: Bird gets 15 points, 7 assists, loud ovation
article.linkText: Jackson, Bird help Storm overshadow Sun
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Back in the state where she had so much success as a collegian, Sue Bird helped the Seattle Storm pick up a narrow victory.

Bird had 15 points, seven assists and made a key steal in the closing seconds of Seattle's 67-65 win over the Connecticut Sun before a sellout crowd of 9,341 Thursday night.

Lauren Jackson scored 20 points, including the winning layup with 3.5 seconds left. Her 3-pointer with 4:52 remaining tied the score at 54-all, and Seattle (11-7) hit eight of 10 free throws down the stretch.

But the focus was on Bird, who helped UConn win NCAA titles in 2000 and 2002.

Dozens of fans wore her No. 10 jersey. Many in the stands cheered loudly at the shootaround, then treated her to an ovation during introductions. Bird grew up on nearby Long Island and had family members watching her for only the second time this season.

"I'd be lying if I told you I didn't have this day circled for a long time," Bird said. "New York is obviously my home. Connecticut is my second home, and Seattle is moving in on third place."

T.J. McWilliams-Franklin led Connecticut with 19 points and 12 rebounds. She scored five in an 11-second span in the closing seconds to give Connecticut (9-11) its final lead at 65-64.

Jackson then took the inbounds pass, drove down court and hit a layup over McWilliams-Franklin. Bird stole the inbounds pass and was fouled, then hit one free throw to close out the scoring.

"I knew they had no timeouts left and they were looking to go," Bird said. "I just stepped in and took it."

McWilliams-Franklin had a chance to win it with under 2 seconds left. She took the inbounds pass near the top of the key and drove inside. Jackson blocked the shot, and McWilliams-Franklin was called for a charge.

Katie Douglas had 18 points and four steals for Connecticut.

The Storm led by as many as 14 in the first half when Simone Edwards' layup made it 22-8. The Seattle post dominated for much of the period, outscoring the Sun 16-6 in the paint and taking a 28-18 lead at the break.

The Sun rallied and took their first lead of the game, 50-49, on a basket by Jessie Hicks with 7:21 left.
